                <p>Mr. Castellan smiled. It was not a nice smile.</p>

                <p>"Give me the books," he said.</p>

                <p>"No," said Professor Winters. She held the box tight.</p>

                <p>"They belong in a museum," said Dad. "Not in your house."</p>

                <p>Mr. Castellan laughed. "Who will stop me? I have two big men. You have a child."</p>

                <p>Finn felt scared. But then he had an idea.</p>

                <p>"Dad," he whispered. "Your phone. Take a photo!"</p>

                <p>Dad understood! He pulled out his phone. Click! He took a photo of Mr. Castellan.</p>

                <p>"What are you doing?" said Mr. Castellan.</p>

                <p>"Taking photos," said Dad. Click! Click! "Of you. And your men. And the books. If you take the books, I will show these photos to the police."</p>

                <p>Mr. Castellan's face went red. "You can't prove anything!"</p>

                <p>"Yes I can," said Professor Winters. She held up a piece of paper. "This is a letter. From the museum. It says we have permission to dig here. You don't. You are trespassing. That means you shouldn't be here."</p>

                <p>"And," said Tom, "we called the police before we came down. They are coming right now. They will be here in ten minutes."</p>

                <p>Mr. Castellan looked angry. Very angry. But he knew he was beaten.</p>

                <p>"This isn't over," he said. He turned and walked back down the tunnel. His two men followed him.</p>

                <p>Everyone was quiet. Then Professor Winters laughed!</p>

                <p>"We did it!" she said. "We saved the books!"</p>

                <p>They heard a noise from above. Voices!</p>

                <p>"Hello? Anyone down there?"</p>

                <p>"It's the police!" said Dad.</p>

                <p>They all went up. Out into the daylight. Two police officers were there.</p>

                <p>Dad told them everything. About Mr. Castellan. About the books. About the tunnel.</p>

                <p>The police looked at the books. "These need to go to the museum right away," said one officer. "For safekeeping."</p>

                <p>"Yes," said Professor Winters. "That's what we want."</p>

                <p>The police took the books. They were very careful. They put them in a special box.</p>

                <p>"You did a good thing," the police officer said to Finn. "You were brave. And you helped save something very special."</p>

                <p>Finn felt proud.</p>

                <p>Two days later, Finn and Dad went home. The lighthouse was fixed. The books were safe in the museum.</p>

                <p>But before they left, Professor Winters came to say goodbye.</p>

                <p>"Thank you," she said. "You saved history. These books will be in the museum. Children will learn from them. For hundreds of years. Because of you."</p>

                <p>She gave Finn a present. It was a book. With pictures of the old manuscripts in it.</p>

                <p>"So you can remember," she said.</p>

                <p>Finn smiled. He would never forget his adventure at Blackrock Lighthouse.</p>
            </div>

